\nReactant aromatic system: `C1=C(C=CC2=C1CCC3C2CCC4(C3CCC4=O)C)OC` - this is the ring with OC (methoxy) substituent.\n\nSo in the reactant, N:21 is bonded to:\n- H:20\n- The aromatic ring (at position where C1 is)\n- OCH3 (methoxy on nitrogen)  \n- N=O\n\nIn the product, the aromatic ring has `=C4[NH:21]N=O)OC` - so N:21 is bonded to:\n- H (but not H:20)\n- The aromatic ring (at C4)\n- N=O\n\nAnd OC is on the ring (methoxy on the aromatic ring).\n\nSo the transformation is:\n1. H:20 transfers from N:21 to O:10 (water → hydronium)\n2. The OCH3 group is removed from N:21 (N-OCH3 bond breaks)\n3. N:21 loses its positive charge\n\nThe reaction center is the cleavage of the N-OCH3 bond on the nitrosamine nitrogen, with proton transfer from N:21 to water.\n\nActually, this looks like a denitrosamine/demethylation reaction. The N-nitroso-N-methylaniline type compound undergoes hydrolysis where:\n- The N-CH3 (or N-OCH3) bond breaks\n- A proton transfers from nitrogen to water\n\nWait, let me re-examine. The OC attached to N:21 in the reactant - is it OCH3 or just O-C(ring)?\n\nLooking at: `[NH+:21](C1=C(C=CC2=C1CCC3C2CCC4(C3CCC4=O)C)OC)N=O`\n\nThe parentheses suggest N:21 is bonded to:\n1. C1=C(...)OC - this whole aromatic system\n2. N=O\n\nBut wait, the OC at the end - is it part of the aromatic ring system or a separate substituent on N?\n\nIn SMILES parsing: `C1=C(C=CC2=C1CCC3C2CCC4(C3CCC4=O)C)OC`\n\nThis is: C1=C(C=CC2=C1...)OC - the OC is a substituent on the ring (at the carbon adjacent to C1).\n\nSo N:21 is bonded to the aromatic ring carbon and N=O, plus H:20. There's no separate OCH3 on nitrogen.\n\nHmm, but then what changes? Let me look at the product more carefully.\n\nProduct: `CC12CCC3C(C1CCC2=O)CCC4=C3C=CC(=C4[NH:21]N=O)OC`\n\nSo in the product, the aromatic ring has:\n- `[NH:21]N=O` at one position\n- `OC` (methoxy) at another position\n\nIn the reactant, the aromatic ring also has OC as a substituent.\n\nSo the main change is:\n- Reactant: H:20-NH+:21(aromatic)N=O (protonated nitrosamine)\n- Product: H:21-N(aromatic)N=O (neutral nitrosamine) + H:20-OH2+:10 (hydronium)\n\nThe reaction center is: H:20 transfers from N:21 to O:10, and N:21 loses its positive charge.\n\nThis is essentially a deprotonation of the protonated nitrosamine by water.\n\nThe reaction center bonds/atoms:\n- H:20-N:21 bond breaks\n- H:20-O:10 bond forms\n- N:21 charge changes from +1 to 0\n\nSo the reaction center is: N:21-H:20 → O:10-H:20, with N:21 losing a proton to water.\n\nIn compact form: N:21-H:20 bond cleaved, O:10-H:20 bond formed; N:21 deprotonation by H2O.\n\nLet me format this as a reaction edit summary:\n\nBond changes:\n- Break: N:21-H:20\n- Form: O:10-H:20\n\nCharge changes:\n- N:21: +1 → 0\n- O:10: 0 → +1 (in H3O+)\n\nThis is a proton transfer from protonated N-nitrosoamine to water."
